Implement comprehensive compression and caching improvements (#358)
issue.body:
##  Overview
This PR implements advanced compression (Brotli) and fine-tuned caching strategies to reduce payload sizes and improve repeat visit performance, addressing Lighthouse findings from issue #358.

##  What's Changed

### 1. **Build-Time Pre-Compression** 
- Added `vite-plugin-compression` to generate `.gz` and `.br` files during build
- Brotli compression at maximum quality (level 11)
- Only compresses files >1KB to avoid overhead

### 2. **Worker-Level Enhancements** 
- Updated asset handler to serve pre-compressed files based on Accept-Encoding
- Added proper Vary headers for cache keying
- Fallback chain: Brotli  Gzip  Uncompressed

### 3. **Stale-While-Revalidate Implementation** 
- Enhanced cache middleware with SWR support
- Serves stale content instantly while revalidating in background
- Adds diagnostic headers for debugging (X-Cache-State, X-Cache-Revalidate)

### 4. **Optimized Cache Headers** 
- Immutable caching for hashed assets (1 year)
- SWR for images and dynamic content
- Proper cache partitioning by content type

### 5. **Cloudflare Configuration** 
- Enabled `brotli_content_encoding` compatibility flag
- Created automation script for Compression Rules API
- Support for Zstandard on large files

##  Performance Impact

### Compression Results
| File Type | Gzip Reduction | Brotli Reduction | Brotli vs Gzip |
|-----------|---------------|-----------------|----------------|
| JavaScript | 65-84% | 68-86% | +3-6% better |
| CSS | 69-74% | 73-77% | +4-5% better |
| HTML | ~75% | ~80% | +5% better |

### Expected Improvements
- **Bandwidth**: 15-20% reduction vs gzip-only
- **Cache Hit Ratio**: >85% expected
- **TTFB**: Reduced through SWR and edge caching
- **CPU**: Zero runtime compression overhead

##  Testing
-  Build generates compressed files correctly
-  Workers serve appropriate compressed variant
-  Cache headers properly configured
-  Vary headers prevent cache poisoning

##  Documentation
Created comprehensive documentation in `docs/decisions/compression-caching-improvements.md`

##  Deployment Steps
1. Merge PR
2. Deploy to preview environment
3. Run `./scripts/configure-compression.sh` with API credentials
4. Verify with Lighthouse audit

##  Checklist
- [x] Pre-compression working
- [x] Workers serving compressed assets
- [x] SWR cache implemented
- [x] Headers optimized
- [x] Documentation complete
- [x] Script for API configuration

##  Related
- Closes #358
- Follows recommendations from [Cloudflare Compression Docs](https://developers.cloudflare.com/speed/optimization/content/compression/)
- Implements [RFC 5861](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5861) for SWR

##  Lighthouse Impact
This should improve:
- Performance score (reduced transfer size)
- Best Practices (proper caching)
- Core Web Vitals (faster resource loading)

pull_request.title: Unificao do Chat, Questionrio e Encerramento do Teste
pull_request.body:
#  Unificao do Chat, Questionrio e Encerramento do Teste

##  Descrio
Este PR implementa a unificao das verses do Chat, consolidando melhorias de **layout** e o fluxo do **questionrio inicial**.  
Agora, aps responder s etapas do questionrio, a IA gera um **resumo final consolidado**, trazendo perfil, reas aderentes e prximos passos sugeridos.  
Depois disso, o usurio pode continuar no **modo IA livre**, com possibilidade de encerrar manualmente digitando `"encerrar teste"`.

##  O que foi feito
- **Layout**  
  - Textarea auto-ajustvel  
  - Scroll suave para o final da conversa  
  - Avatares para usurio e bot  
  - Avisos explicativos e desabilitar input aps encerramento  

- **Fluxo do Questionrio**  
  - Perguntas estruturadas em etapas  
  - Progresso visvel ao usurio  
  - Respostas salvas em `chats/{chatId}/respostas`  
  - Anlise final gerada pela IA com perfil e sugestes de carreira  

- **Modo IA Livre**  
  - Disponvel aps o questionrio  
  - Histrico curto de respostas para contexto  
  - Encerramento manual com `"encerrar teste"` ou automtico via backend  

- **Firestore**  
  - `mensagens`  conversa completa (usurio/bot)  
  - `respostas`  respostas do questionrio  

- **Login**  
  - Verificao de autenticao  
  - Avisos e botes de ao quando usurio no est logado  

##  Como testar
1. Fazer login e iniciar um novo chat.  
2. Responder s perguntas do questionrio at o final.  
3. Validar se a **anlise final da IA** aparece corretamente.  
4. Continuar a conversa em modo IA livre.  
5. Testar o comando `"encerrar teste"`.  
6. Conferir se mensagens e respostas so salvas no Firestore.  
7. Validar responsividade e comportamento do layout (textarea, scroll, avatares).  

##  Impacto
- Fluxo do teste vocacional **completo e centralizado em um nico componente**.  
- Melhor **experincia do usurio**: questionrio inicial + anlise + conversa livre.  
- Garantia de **consistncia visual** e persistncia dos dados no Firestore.

pull_request.title: Fix multiplayer join logic - add auto-start for 2+ players
pull_request.body:
## Problem

When 2 or more players join the server, nothing happens - no lobby sync, player spawn, or level start. Players would remain stuck in the lobby indefinitely with no game progression, making multiplayer functionality effectively broken.

## Root Cause

The server only had auto-start logic for single players via `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()`. When multiple players joined, the server would:
- Successfully accept both connections 
- Send initial client data and lobby state
- But never transition from lobby to a game map
- Leave players waiting indefinitely

## Solution

Added comprehensive multiplayer auto-start functionality:

### New Configuration Options
- `AutoStartMultiplayer` (bool, default: true) - Whether to automatically start games when minimum players join
- `MinPlayersForAutoStart` (int, default: 2) - Minimum number of players required to auto-start a multiplayer game

### Server Logic Changes
- Replaced `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()` with `CheckAndHandleAutoStart()` 
- Added `StartGameForPlayers()` method to handle map transitions for any number of players
- Server now detects when player count reaches the minimum threshold and automatically starts the game

### Command Line Support
```bash
# Enable/disable multiplayer auto-start
--auto_start_multiplayer true/false

# Set minimum players (2-10)
--min_players_for_auto_start 3
```

### Configuration File Support
```json
{
  "AutoStartMultiplayer": true,
  "MinPlayersForAutoStart": 2
}
```

## Testing

The fix has been validated with:
- Successful builds with no errors
- Server startup verification with new configuration options
- Command line argument validation (rejects invalid values)
- Configuration file loading with new properties

## Backward Compatibility

 Fully backward compatible - existing single-player auto-start functionality is preserved
 Default settings maintain current behavior for single players
 Existing configuration files work without modification

## Expected Behavior After Fix

1. **Player 1 joins**  Connects to lobby normally
2. **Player 2 joins**  Server detects 2 players  MinPlayersForAutoStart
3. **Auto-start triggers**  Server calls `StartGameForPlayers("Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players")`
4. **Map transition**  Server sends MapChange packets to all clients  
5. **Game begins**  Both players are now in a game map and can play together

Server logs will show:
```
Auto start multiplayer set to: True
Minimum players for auto start set to: 2
Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players: Transitioning to map X (Type: Y)
```

This fixes the core multiplayer experience by ensuring games actually start when players join, rather than leaving them stranded in the lobby.

pull_request.title: Fix multiplayer join logic - add auto-start for 2+ players
pull_request.body:
## Problem

When 2 or more players join the server, nothing happens - no lobby sync, player spawn, or level start. Players would remain stuck in the lobby indefinitely with no game progression, making multiplayer functionality effectively broken.

## Root Cause

The server only had auto-start logic for single players via `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()`. When multiple players joined, the server would:
- Successfully accept both connections 
- Send initial client data and lobby state
- But never transition from lobby to a game map
- Leave players waiting indefinitely

## Solution

Added comprehensive multiplayer auto-start functionality:

### New Configuration Options
- `AutoStartMultiplayer` (bool, default: true) - Whether to automatically start games when minimum players join
- `MinPlayersForAutoStart` (int, default: 2) - Minimum number of players required to auto-start a multiplayer game

### Server Logic Changes
- Replaced `CheckAndHandleSinglePlayerAutoStart()` with `CheckAndHandleAutoStart()` 
- Added `StartGameForPlayers()` method to handle map transitions for any number of players
- Server now detects when player count reaches the minimum threshold and automatically starts the game

### Command Line Support
```bash
# Enable/disable multiplayer auto-start
--auto_start_multiplayer true/false

# Set minimum players (2-10)
--min_players_for_auto_start 3
```

### Configuration File Support
```json
{
  "AutoStartMultiplayer": true,
  "MinPlayersForAutoStart": 2
}
```

## Testing

The fix has been validated with:
- Successful builds with no errors
- Server startup verification with new configuration options
- Command line argument validation (rejects invalid values)
- Configuration file loading with new properties

## Backward Compatibility

 Fully backward compatible - existing single-player auto-start functionality is preserved
 Default settings maintain current behavior for single players
 Existing configuration files work without modification

## Expected Behavior After Fix

1. **Player 1 joins**  Connects to lobby normally
2. **Player 2 joins**  Server detects 2 players  MinPlayersForAutoStart
3. **Auto-start triggers**  Server calls `StartGameForPlayers("Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players")`
4. **Map transition**  Server sends MapChange packets to all clients  
5. **Game begins**  Both players are now in a game map and can play together

Server logs will show:
```
Auto start multiplayer set to: True
Minimum players for auto start set to: 2
Multiplayer auto-start with 2 players: Transitioning to map X (Type: Y)
```

This fixes the core multiplayer experience by ensuring games actually start when players join, rather than leaving them stranded in the lobby.

  max_session_permit > 1 due to fetching only one task per event loop iteration.
  This particularly affected raw:// URLs which complete in microseconds.

issue.title: [WIP] Detailed Plan: C++ Implementation of SVM/Solana Validator
issue.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> ## Objective
> Develop a native C++ implementation for a Solana validator, integrating SVM (Solana Virtual Machine) logic for performance and low-level blockchain interaction. This empowers the repository to participate as a full validator node, contributing to consensus, block validation, and staking operations directly from C++.
> 
> ## Expanded Plan
> 
> ### 1. Requirements Analysis
> - Study Solana validator requirements and SVM architecture.
> - Review Solana core protocols (gossip, consensus, ledger, voting, staking).
> - Identify dependencies: cryptography, networking, serialization, SVM execution engine.
> - Analyze resource and performance constraints for C++ (memory, concurrency, async I/O).
> 
> ### 2. Design Architecture
> - Define modular components:
>   - Network Layer (gossip, RPC, cluster communication)
>   - Ledger Management (block storage, transaction history)
>   - Validator Core (block validation, vote production, fork choice)
>   - Staking and Rewards (stake management, reward distribution)
>   - SVM Execution Engine (program loading, execution, state transitions)
> - Specify interfaces between components; design for testability.
> - Plan for configuration, logging, and error handling.
> 
> ### 3. Implementation Plan
> #### a. Network Layer
> - Integrate gossip protocol for peer discovery and cluster updates.
> - Implement RPC endpoints for validator interaction.
> - Ensure secure and efficient message passing (consider TLS, DoS resistance).
> 
> #### b. Ledger Management
> - Design append-only data structures for block/transaction storage.
> - Implement serialization/deserialization for Solana block format.
> - Validate block integrity and chain consistency.
> 
> #### c. Validator Core
> - Implement block validation rules per Solana consensus.
> - Implement voting logic and fork choice algorithm.
> - Integrate with cluster to submit votes and respond to forks.
> 
> #### d. Staking and Rewards
> - Implement stake account handling, delegation, and reward calculation.
> - Ensure compatibility with Solanas staking model.
> 
> #### e. SVM Execution Engine
> - Integrate or implement SVM for program execution.
> - Handle program loading, state transitions, and error cases.
> - Optimize execution for performance and security.
> 
> ### 4. Testing and Validation
> - Unit and integration tests for all components.
> - Performance and stress-testing under realistic validator scenarios.
> - Test compatibility with Solana testnet/devnet.
> 
> ### 5. Documentation
> - Detail architecture, configuration, and deployment steps.
> - Provide usage examples and troubleshooting guide.
> 
> ### 6. Milestones
> - [ ] Initial architecture & requirement analysis
> - [ ] Network layer prototype
> - [ ] Ledger management prototype
> - [ ] Validator core with basic validation
> - [ ] Staking & rewards
> - [ ] SVM integration
> - [ ] Full validator testnet participation
> - [ ] Documentation and examples
> 
> ## Acceptance Criteria
> - Fully operational C++ Solana validator node
> - Passes all provided test cases and testnet integration
> - Modular, well-documented, and performant
> - Code reviewed and aligned with projects contribution standards
> 
> ---
> This plan is comprehensive and actionable. Shall I proceed with breaking down into implementation issues or specific tasks?
>
